# Integrating Claude into Next.js with Streaming

Here's the simplest approach using the Anthropic SDK:

## 1. Install the SDK

```bash
npm install @anthropic-ai/sdk
```

## 2. Create an API Route

**`app/api/chat/route.js`** (or `.ts`):

```javascript
import Anthropic from "@anthropic-ai/sdk";

const client = new Anthropic();

export async function POST(request) {
  const { messages, userContext } = await request.json();

  const stream = await client.messages.stream({
    model: "claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022",
    max_tokens: 1024,
    system: `You are a helpful assistant analyzing user data. 
Context: ${userContext}`,
    messages: messages,
  });

  // Create a ReadableStream for real-time streaming
  const readable = stream.toReadableStream();
  return new Response(readable, {
    headers: {
      "Content-Type": "text/event-stream",
      "Cache-Control": "no-cache",
      Connection: "keep-alive",
    },
  });
}
```

## 3. Client-Side Component

**`app/components/ChatInterface.jsx`**:

```jsx
"use client";

import { useState } from "react";

export default function ChatInterface() {
  const [input, setInput] = useState("");
  const [messages, setMessages] = useState([]);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);

  const handleSubmit = async (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    if (!input.trim()) return;

    // Add user message
    const userMessage = { role: "user", content: input };
    setMessages((prev) => [...prev, userMessage]);
    setLoading(true);
    setInput("");

    try {
      const response = await fetch("/api/chat", {
        method: "POST",
        headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
        body: JSON.stringify({
          messages: [...messages, userMessage],
          userContext: "User's data context here",
        }),
      });

      const reader = response.body.getReader();
      const decoder = new TextDecoder();
      let fullResponse = "";

      // Stream in chunks
      while (true) {
        const { done, value } = await reader.read();
        if (done) break;

        const chunk = decoder.decode(value);
        fullResponse += chunk;

        // Update UI with streamed content
        setMessages((prev) => {
          const updated = [...prev];
          const lastMsg = updated[updated.length - 1];
          if (lastMsg?.role === "assistant") {
            lastMsg.content = fullResponse;
          } else {
            updated.push({ role: "assistant", content: fullResponse });
          }
          return updated;
        });
      }
    } catch (error) {
      console.error("Error:", error);
    } finally {
      setLoading(false);
    }
  };

  return (
    <div className="flex flex-col h-screen">
      <div className="flex-1 overflow-y-auto p-4 space-y-4">
        {messages.map((msg, i) => (
          <div
            key={i}
            className={`p-3 rounded ${
              msg.role === "user"
                ? "bg-blue-500 text-white ml-auto max-w-md"
                : "bg-gray-200 max-w-md"
            }`}
          >
            {msg.content}
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <form onSubmit={handleSubmit} className="p-4 border-t">
        <div className="flex gap-2">
          <input
            type="text"
            value={input}
            onChange={(e) => setInput(e.target.value)}
            placeholder="Ask about your data..."
            disabled={loading}
            className="flex-1 p-2 border rounded"
          />
          <button
            type="submit"
            disabled={loading}
            className="px-4 py-2 bg-blue-500 text-white rounded disabled:opacity-50"
          >
            Send
          </button>
        </div>
      </form>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## 4. Environment Setup

**`.env.local`**:

```
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=your_key_here
```

## Key Points

- **Streaming**: The SDK's `.toReadableStream()` makes streaming trivial
- **No complex setup**: Just API key + SDK
- **Real-time UX**: Users see responses appear character-by-character
- **Secure**: API calls happen server-side, key never exposed to client

## Optional Enhancements

- Add rate limiting middleware
- Store conversation history in a database
- Add context injection from your actual data
- Implement error boundaries and retry logic
- Use `max_tokens` to control response length

This is production-ready for most use cases. For complex multi-turn conversations with memory, consider adding a database layer later.

# Guaranteed JSON Schema Compliance

You can use Claude's **JSON mode** with the `json_schema` parameter to get guaranteed schema compliance. Here's how:

## Basic Setup

```python
import anthropic
import json

client = anthropic.Anthropic()

schema = {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
        "name": {"type": "string"},
        "age": {"type": "integer"},
        "email": {"type": "string", "format": "email"}
    },
    "required": ["name", "age", "email"],
    "additionalProperties": False
}

message = client.messages.create(
    model="claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022",
    max_tokens=1024,
    thinking={
        "type": "enabled",
        "budget_tokens": 1024
    },
    response_format={
        "type": "json_schema",
        "json_schema": {
            "name": "UserProfile",
            "schema": schema,
            "strict": True
        }
    },
    messages=[
        {
            "role": "user",
            "content": "Create a user profile for Alice who is 30 years old with email alice@example.com"
        }
    ]
)

print(message.content[0].text)
```

## Key Requirements

| Parameter | Purpose |
|-----------|---------|
| `"strict": True` | **Enforces** schema compliance (not best-effort) |
| `json_schema` | Defines your schema using JSON Schema format |
| `"type": "json_schema"` | Enables the feature |

## What "Strict" Means

With `strict: True`:
- ✅ Output **always** matches your schema exactly
- ✅ No extra fields or type mismatches
- ✅ Claude cannot add commentary or deviate
- ❌ Request fails if schema cannot be satisfied

## Important Notes

1. **Models**: Works with Claude 3.5 Sonnet and newer
2. **Schema Requirements**: Your schema must be valid JSON Schema (Draft 2020-12)
3. **Validation**: Claude validates before responding; invalid requests error rather than bend the schema
4. **Limitations**: Avoid overly restrictive enums or impossible constraints

## Example with Complex Schema

```python
schema = {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
        "results": {
            "type": "array",
            "items": {
                "type": "object",
                "properties": {
                    "id": {"type": "integer"},
                    "status": {"enum": ["active", "inactive"]},
                    "metadata": {"type": "object"}
                },
                "required": ["id", "status"],
                "additionalProperties": False
            }
        }
    },
    "required": ["results"],
    "additionalProperties": False
}
```

This is the most reliable way to guarantee schema compliance—Claude cannot deviate from strict schemas.

# Preventing Unnecessary Re-renders in React

Here are the main solutions, from simplest to most advanced:

## 1. **React.memo** (Functional Components)
Memoizes your component and only re-renders if props change:

```jsx
const MyComponent = React.memo(({ name, age }) => {
  return <div>{name} - {age}</div>;
});
```

By default, it does a shallow comparison of props. For custom logic:

```jsx
const MyComponent = React.memo(
  ({ name, age }) => <div>{name} - {age}</div>,
  (prevProps, nextProps) => {
    return prevProps.name === nextProps.name; // return true if equal (skip render)
  }
);
```

## 2. **useMemo** (For Expensive Operations)
Memoize values to prevent child re-renders:

```jsx
function Parent({ data }) {
  const memoizedData = useMemo(() => data, [data]);
  return <Child data={memoizedData} />;
}
```

## 3. **useCallback** (For Function Props)
Memoize callback functions so child components don't re-render:

```jsx
function Parent() {
  const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
    console.log('clicked');
  }, []); // empty deps = function never changes

  return <Child onClick={handleClick} />;
}
```

## 4. **PureComponent** (Class Components)
Automatically does shallow prop/state comparison:

```jsx
class MyComponent extends React.PureComponent {
  render() {
    return <div>{this.props.name}</div>;
  }
}
```

## 5. **shouldComponentUpdate** (Class Components)
Fine-grained control over re-renders:

```jsx
class MyComponent extends React.Component {
  shouldComponentUpdate(nextProps, nextState) {
    return this.props.id !== nextProps.id;
  }
  render() { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Quick Decision Tree

| Situation | Solution |
|-----------|----------|
| Child re-renders on parent update | `React.memo` |
| Passing objects/arrays as props | `useMemo` |
| Passing callbacks as props | `useCallback` |
| Complex comparison logic | Custom memo comparator |

**⚠️ Common Pitfall:** Objects/arrays created in render always look "new" to comparisons:

```jsx
// ❌ Bad - new object every render
<Child data={{ name: "John" }} />

// ✅ Good - memoized
const data = useMemo(() => ({ name: "John" }), []);
<Child data={data} />
```

